l ascendancy and domestically through an exploration of the social formation of Filipino communities in the United States. He reveals how American practices of racial exclusion repeatedly collided with the imperatives of U.S. overseas expansion. A unique portrait of the Filipino American experience, The Third Asiatic Invasion links the Filipino experience to that of Puerto Ricans, Mexicans, Chinese and Native Americans, among others, revealing how the politics of exclusion played out over time against different population groups.Weaving together an impressive range of materials-including newspapers, government reports, legal documents and archival sources-into a seamless narrative, Baldoz illustrates how the quixotic status of Filipinos played a significant role in transforming the politics of race, immigration and nationality in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aFilipino AmericansxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aBaldoz. 4aFilipinos. 4aUS. 4aWeaving. 4aarchival. 4adocuments. 4agovernment. 4aillustrates. 4aimmigration. 4aincluding. 4ainto. 4alegal. 4amaterials. 4anarrative. 4anationality. 4anewspapers. 4aplayed. 4aquixotic. 4arace. 4arange. 4areports. 4arole. 4aseamless. 4asignificant. 4asources. 4astatus. 4atogether. 4atransforming. 4awide. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814789889423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814789889.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_S